<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<blockquote>
<title> TV Ratings </title>
<br>
<center><h2> TV Ratings&#58; A Fine Mess </h2></center>
<p>
The television ratings system has been in effect only since January 1, yet there's already plenty of evidence it's doing a poor job of informing parents about which programs are suitable, and which unsuitable, for their children.
<p>
So far, the most obvious flaw has to do with the treatment of sexual content. The networks, which rate their own offerings, repeatedly have given to racy shows ratings that indicate those shows are fine for youngsters. The following episodes were rated TV-PG, meaning "parental guidance [is] suggested the program may contain infrequent coarse language, limited violence, [and] some suggestive sexual dialogue and situations."  Given the sort of content we're talking about, that would seem much too mild a warning.
<p>
Take the January 6 "Ink," on CBS. This episode of the newspaper sitcom centered on a madam and her little black book. One reporter exulted, "This story has everything! Sex in a car, sex after lunch, sex under water." Another reporter reminisced about the time in boarding school when she "sold pictures of the gym teacher doing it with the headmaster." The next night, ABC's "Life's Work" contained jokes about a man who masturbated by rubbing against a tree.
<p>
NBC's night for smut was January 8. On "Wings," a character discussed how he and his girlfriend made love four times a day, and mentioned that the previous night, "we did it on the hood of my El Camino." On "Chicago Sons," a character expressed his desire to invite an attractive female colleague to a bed-and-breakfast, "where we'll eat pralines off each other's naked bodies."
<p>
The next night on NBC, "Friends" had one character talking about how depressed he was when he saw a woman he'd just split up with "just walkin' with her friend Donna, laughin' and talkin'. It killed me." His roommate replied, "Yes, but you ended up having sex with both of them that afternoon."
<p>
All those series air in the so-called family hour, between 8 and 9 p.m. Post-9 o'clock programming was raunchy as well: on January 8, NBC's "Men Behaving Badly" included a woman's reference to "fifty-five hours of nonstop sex" with a man she'd just met. "Men Behaving Badly" was rated, you guessed it, TV-PG. 
<p>
</body>
</html>
