HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Sunday, 09-Feb-97 19:49:52 GMT
Last-modified: Tuesday, 17-Sep-96 18:30:02 GMT
Content-length: 11502
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>CyberAlert 09/11/96</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<blockquote>
<center><img src="/mrc/images/checkbox.gif">
<h2>***Media Research Center CyberAlert***</h2>
<i>09/11/96</i><p>
<p>
</center>
<center><a href="#cover"> Front cover of the September 11, 1996 report:</a> | <a href="#best">Best and Worst, from page 2 of the 15 page report</a>
</center>
<p>
One item today: Wednesday morning at 10am the MRC will hold
a press conference with MRC Chairman L. Brent Bozell to release
our final Media Reality Check  96 report on TV network coverage
of the conventions. C-SPAN should be there to tape the press
conference, so you may be able to see it Wednesday night.<p>

    Below are the front page summary and page 2 explantion of
the best and worst networks and reporters. If you'd like to get
the entire 15-page report which includes tables, graphs and
network by network examples of labeling, agenda questions and
the disparity in the highlighting of negativity, please send an
e-mail to me: bbaker@mediaresearch.org (or reply to this e-mail
address but I may not see it until Wednesday night). Tell me
either your address and we'll snail mail it, or your fax number.
Or, call me at (703) 683-9733. If I'm not in, ask for Carey
Evans and she should be able to fax it to you.<p>  

<center>
<h3><a name="cover">Front</a> cover of the September 11, 1996 report:</h3>


<h4>Final Report on 1996 Television Network Convention Coverage:<br>

TV Analysts Label Democrats Twice as Often, But Fire Liberal
Questions<br>
Both Parties Too Conservative for the Networks</h4>
</center>

    Alexandria, VA -- The television networks substantially
increased the number of labels they applied to Democrats during
their 1996 convention over 1992, but at both the Republican and
Democratic conventions this year the networks demanded answers
to a barrage of questions from the left. For Republicans
gathered in San Diego, GOP intolerance on abortion was the
issue. For Democrats convened in Chicago, going too far to the
right on welfare reform became the media focus. Adding up both
questions and statements made by reporters to one another,
abortion or exclusion of pro-choice voices were raised as an
issue 55 times in San Diego, while viewers heard about welfare
reform 43 times in Chicago.<p>

    After producing a daily Media Reality Check '96 newsletter
during the August political conventions, the Media Research
Center's (MRC) news division staff organized its analysis of
prime time coverage into this special 15-page report. This
analysis covers ABC, CBS, CNN (starting at 8pm ET), NBC and the
joint NBC/PBS broadcast.<p> 

    <b>Key findings:</b><br>
<ul>
 <li>Democrats labeled liberal more often than Republicans tagged
conservative. Studies of the 1984, 1988 and 1992 conventions
found Republicans labeled much more frequently than Democrats.
In 1992, the MRC determined the networks applied 118
conservative labels during the GOP conclave, but just 38 liberal
labels during the Democratic gathering. This year, Republicans
were tagged 59 times (13 moderate, 30 conservative, and 16 more
extremist terms), but Democrats were labeled 119 times (44
moderate, 71 liberal and four more extremist terms).<p>

    In Chicago, Bill Clinton got 28 moderate labels and captured
about half as many liberal tags with 16. In San Diego, the
networks focused most of their labeling on conservative
delegates and speakers as Bob Dole went largely untagged --
three moderate and two conservative labels. The Republican
platform was never called moderate and the Democratic platform
was never described as liberal. See page 3 for a summary table
and graph, pages 6-14 for examples.<p>

<li>Convention attendees pummeled with questions from the left
side of the political spectrum. On 51 occasions in San Diego
Republicans were hit with questions from the left, especially
about intolerance and abortion, but they heard just six
inquiries from the right. Two weeks later instead of questioning
Democrats from the right, the networks posed 47 from the left,
the vast majority on how many Democrats opposed President
Clinton's decision to sign the welfare reform bill, but just 11
questions from the right. In this area the networks have grown
more biased. Four years ago, while the GOP got the same
treatment, hearing 131 questions from the left compared to 17
from the right, Democrats got a more even going over with 46
questions from the left and 38 from the right. See page 4 for a
table and graph, pages 7-15 for examples.<p>

<li>Republicans blamed repeatedly for displaying a negative
tone, but Democrats go unscathed despite some pretty vitriolic
speeches. In San Diego the networks characterized Republicans
with terms like "negative," "harsh," "strident" or "mean" or
described GOP speeches as an "attack," 34 times. Democrats were
hit with the negative descriptions just six times during their
convention, but even in Chicago Republicans got hammered more
with 23 references to GOP negativity. In 1992, the networks
questioned the Republican tone as too negative 70 times, but
never once raised the subject against Democrats at their
convention. See page 5 for a summary table and examples of the
contrast.<p>

<li>Controversies such as Whitewater and Travelgate barely
acknowledged. The Clintons are under active investigation by an
independent counsel, but the networks made only seven references
to Democratic scandals. NBC and the joint NBC-PBS broadcast
aired two mentions; ABC, CBS, and CNN, only one. Topics never
mentioned: the FBI files scandal, the Iran-Bosnia scandal, and
the special counsel investigations of Cabinet members such as
Henry Cisneros and Mike Espy. Controversies about Republicans,
such as questions about Elizabeth Dole's blind trust, were also
ignored.
</ul>

<center>
<h3><a name="best">Best</a> and Worst, from page 2 of the 15 page report:</h3>
</center>

<b>Best Network: ABC News </b><br>
    Posed the fewest ideological questions at both conventions,
had the least disparity in blaming the parties for being too
negative and, given the amount of airtime, were the most willing
to identify Democrats as liberal.<p>

<B>Worst Network: CNN</B><br>
    Failed to take advantage of their added airtime to offer
viewers something beyond just more of what the other networks
showed. CNN had the greatest disparity in the agenda of
questions posed, with 23 from the left to just three from the
right.<p>

<B>Best reporters</B><br>
<ul>
<li><B>Sam Donaldson, ABC News:</B> In San Diego he refrained from
gratuitous attacks on the Republicans for being too intolerant.
In Chicago, on the first day of the convention, Donaldson
offered a balanced appraisal of the party delegates, noting that
the Democratic delegates "are far to the left of the mainstream
just as the Republicans were to the right of the mainstream." In
the midst of hoopla over Bill Clinton's speech, only Donaldson
realized that while he gave a "great speech," the "record shows
that the next day he may give a different speech, change his
mind, trim it a little bit, do something else."<p>

 <li><B>Lisa Myers, NBC News: </B>One of the few reporters to pose
questions from both the left and right. In San Diego, she asked
Senator Kay Bailey Hutchison from the right about how she "has
generally opposed efforts to cut off benefits to illegal
immigrants, particularly education and health benefits. Why
would hardworking American taxpayers pay for people who are here
illegally?" Then she asked her about how people who saw her
speech "found it too negative. They didn't particularly like the
degree to which you attacked the President. In retrospect, do
you think you went too far?" On the first night in Chicago,
Myers quizzed a delegate about whether liberals or New Democrats
control the party.<p> 

 <li><B>Brian Ross, ABC News:</B> Although CNN's Brooks Jackson appeared
early in prime time with stories on corporate contributions and
union influence, ABC's Ross deserves recognition despite the
fact his pieces did not air in prime time. In a series of World
News Tonight stories, Ross went after the big money contributors
to both parties. Ross raised unique issues, such as "the giant
media corporations...very much in the middle of the mix." In San
Diego he noted that "the ABC hospitality suite was a lobbyist's
dream." In Chicago he looked at one big donor: "His name is
Arthur Coia, who despite being president of a labor union the
FBI says has long been controlled by the Mafia...has become one
of the Democrats' top money people."<p>
</ul>

<B>Worst reporters:</B><br>
<ul>
 <li><B>Maria Shriver, NBC News:</B>  Seemed baffled why a rape victim
would have anything to do with the GOP and her interview with
Hillary Clinton following the First Lady's address was more like
two old friends sharing tales of their suffering than a
dispassionate interview. Just after Jan Licence addressed
Republicans about victim's rights, Shriver asked her: "But why
[speak] at a Republican convention? So many people have said
that they don't think this ticket, or perhaps this party, is
supportive of women's issues. Why make this stand here?"
Shriver's interview with the First Lady assumed Mrs. Clinton had
been unfairly attacked by Republicans. Shriver posed questions
like, "This has been a difficult couple of years for you. Did
that applause, the way you've been treated here, the way people
have been reacting to you, kind of make it all go away?" And,
noting GOP criticism of her book, Shriver wondered, "How did
that affect you when you heard about that?"<p>

<li><B>Judy Woodruff, CNN:</B> In San Diego she demanded that
Republicans explain why there weren't more female delegates, but
in Chicago instead of challenging Democrats on the appeal of
their pro-partial birth abortion stand, she worried about
welfare reform going too far. Woodruff peppered Mrs. Clinton
with six welfare questions, all from the left. She pleaded with
her to stop it: "Eleanor Roosevelt, whom you admire, mentioned
her again just now, said that much of the time she kept her
disagreements with the President to herself in private, but
there were times that she felt it was important to disagree
publicly. Does there ever come a time with you, and if not
welfare reform, then what?"<p>

<li><B>Tom Brokaw, NBC News:</B> Found Republican speakers threatened
to be perceived as too mean, took a pot shot at Ronald Reagan,
and portrayed Republicans as insensitive to rape, but praised
the speaking power of Democrats. In San Diego he warned that the
GOP knows "it has to lower the threshold of perceived meanness
on the part of the country." In Chicago, after Jesse Jackson's
speech which attacked conservatives, he admired how his words
grew "out of a very deep passion." Brokaw did at least mention
Whitewater in Chicago, but after the moving tribute to Ronald
Reagan in San Diego he took this swipe: "Ronald Reagan will have
to learn how history will judge his time in office -- the
deficits, the Iran-Contra affair." At the GOP conclave he told
rape victim Jan Licence: "This is a party that is dominated by
men," so, he wondered, "do you think before tonight they ever
thought about what happens in America with rape?"
</ul>

<I>-- Brent Baker</I>
</body>
</html>

</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT15-B12-119</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA034-000683-B006-3</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.empower.org:80/nationalreview/10feb97/week.html 204.71.237.79 19970209194912 text/html 14129
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Sunday, 09-Feb-97 19:50:00 GMT
Last-modified: Monday, 27-Jan-97 22:33:14 GMT
Content-length: 13945
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<BODY bgcolor="#fffff" LINK="red" VLINK="black">
<title>The Week -- February 10, 1997</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/week.gif" ALT="The Week">
</center>
<P>
<center>February 10, 1997</center>
<p>
<HR>
<P>
<!--------------------------------------------------------------------->



<LI>
Why did Rep. Jim McDermott go through all the trouble of intercepting Republicans' phone calls with a scanner, when he could have just looked up the transcripts in their FBI files?
<P>
<hr>
<P>

<LI>Spectators shivered, the choir sang ``Amazing Grace'' and ``America,'' and William Jefferson Clinton was sworn in at the nation's 53rd presidential inaugural. In a speech which, for all its brevity, was heavy with boilerplate, Mr. Clinton did enounce his political position. ``Government is not the problem, and government is not the solution. . . . We need a government humble enough not to solve all our problems for us, but strong enough to give us the tools to solve our problems for ourselves.'' Possession-theories of his political success ignore his characteristic tropism toward a pragmatic-sounding centrism, a spot to the right of left. In practice, Clintonism may be as porous as a colander (what tools? what problems?). But the political counterarguments have to be made. If Clinton's enemies will not make them, they face a frustrating four years.


<P>
<hr>
<P>
<LI>When Congress passed the welfare bill last year, skeptics warned that Republican governors, chafing under the bill's work provisions and spending restraints, would become a major obstacle to its implementation. Sure enough, GOP governors led by George W. Bush (Tex.) are already agitating to reverse the bill's cutoff of Supplemental Security Income benefits for legal immigrants. Any backtracking on this provision would be a substantive and political disaster. There are now more aged non-citizens than citizens on SSI; the number of non-citizens on SSI has exploded from 370,000 in 1989 to more than 800,000 today as immigrants have taken advantage of this welfare spigot. Republicans were right to shut it off. Moreover, any fiddling with the SSI provision will go through the Senate Finance Committee, where Republicans have nominal control only (liberal Sens. Jim Jeffords and John Chafee account for the GOP's two-vote margin on the committee), which means that any changes on SSI will be accompanied by other ``fixes,'' such as expansions of Medicaid coverage and new mandates on the states. Congressional Republicans should send a clear message to their brethren in the governors' mansions: Hands off welfare reform.

<P>
<hr>
<P>

<LI>The new welfare bill limits the amount of food stamps that able-bodied, childless adults under age fifty who work less than twenty hours a week may receive. New York Gov. George Pataki has not sought a waiver to stop these cuts in his state, prompting this dispatch from the <I>New York Times</I>: ``Advocates for the poor and religious leaders . . . are particularly disturbed, they say, because food stamps, unlike other welfare programs, are paid for solely by the Federal Government.'' Liz Krueger, associate director of the Community Food Resource Center, asks, ``Isn't the job of a governor to make sure he maximizes federal revenues?'' Isn't that in one of the <I>Federalist Papers</I>?


<P>
<hr>
<P>
<LI>Proponents of tax reform have from time to time questioned the political wisdom of trying to reform the tax code with one bill. A proposal by Alan Reynolds and Stephen Moore transforms the politics of tax reform by applying the free-market principles of choice and competition. They would leave the current tax code alone, but allow anyone to opt out by paying an ``alternative maximum tax,'' or MaxTax, of 25 per cent (with only one break, a credit for payroll taxes paid). It would be impossible to claim that this flat tax would raise <I>anybody's</I> taxes, and it would lower tax rates for millions of Americans. In addition, the difficult transition problems that have concerned technical analysts of tax reform would melt away. (Deductions would not have to be phased out; they would simply become optional.) Reynolds and Moore have managed to marry policy wonkery, political savvy, and conceptual elegance.
<P>
<hr>
<P>

<LI>To clear his name (and do some good) after the Christine Keeler sex scandal, disgraced British war minister John Profumo worked for three decades with underprivileged boys in London's East End. Spiro Agnew waited 21 years before his bust was installed in the Capitol alongside those of the other former Vice Presidents. To restore his own reputation as a brilliant political advisor, fetishist and adulterer Dick Morris required six days, and he now dominates the Sunday-morning talk shows, where he promotes his 359-page memoir. If present trends continue, public officials caught in ethical scandals will some day need no rehabilitation time at all. For instance, a President convincingly accused of sexual harassment might skip directly over the damaging allegations and proceed with the duties of his office as if nothing had happened.

<P>
<hr>
<P>

<LI>Five months after becoming two of the first four women to enter the Citadel, Misses Messer and Mentavlos are leaving. They were forced to sing obscene songs and drink iced tea until they vomited; their sweatshirts were doused with nail-polish remover and ignited. But this is just this kind of behavior that has made the Citadel famous. As appalling as it may seem, setting freshmen on fire is apparently a tradition in Echo company, of which the girls were members. In her farewell statement, Miss Mentavlos asked her male classmates to ``take a long look at how they view their girlfriends, wives, mothers, sisters, and daughters.'' However, by attending the Citadel, Miss Mentavlos endeavored to remove herself from those categories, and from the respect accorded to them. It seems that her fellow students indulged her.
<P>
<hr>
<P>


<LI>In his syndicated <I>Washington Post</I> column, Mark Shields teases <I>NR</I> and the <I>Wall Street Journal</I> editorial page for having made ``bum predictions'' about the bad effects of President Clinton's 1993 tax increases. Shields's rebuttal consists of listing positive economic trends that followed the tax increase, which he assumes must therefore have been caused by it. Those trends could use some perspective. The President's vaunted ``11 million jobs'' amounts to 1.9 per cent growth each year -- roughly the average rate for the last 25 years, <I>including recessions</I>. It's a far cry from the 2.4 per cent annual job growth registered during the low-tax years of 1983 - 89. Interest rates were falling globally before Clinton's tax; they reversed course soon after it passed, and resumed falling only around the time the Republicans took Congress. The deficit is down mostly because of that fall in interest rates, plus reckless defense cuts and the winding down of the S&L bailout. Tax revenues have increased because of the economic upswing that was well under way when Clinton was elected, but compared to the pre - tax-hike years, revenues are a smaller proportion of an economy that is growing more slowly. And Shields is counting his chickens too soon: the final installment of Clinton's tax hike came in April 1996. Already there are signs that the economy is running out both of workers and of savings. (If the Administration responds by trying to talk the dollar down, get ready for a hard landing.) Shields concluded his column: ``It doesn't hurt to admit publicly you have been wrong.'' Tell it to the President.
<P>
<hr>
<P>


<LI>In the ongoing battle over Wisconsin's schoolchildren, a state judge, Paul Higginbotham, has again blocked the use of state funds for a voucher program that includes religious schools. His ruling acknowledged the ``sad plight of Milwaukee's public-school system'' (``sad'' is a mild word for a system in which only one-third of the students entering high school -- and only one-quarter of the black students -- graduate). But Judge Higginbotham found, predictably, that using tax dollars for anything connected however remotely with religion was unconstitutional -- ignoring the facts that a) nowadays, the religious content in most parochial schools is distinctly secondary; and b) the public schools themselves inculcate a religion, though not one having anything to do with the God of anyone's fathers. Judge Higginbotham's word is not the last one: the Milwaukee-based Parents for School Choice will take the case all the way to the Supreme Court if necessary; meanwhile PAVE (Partners Advancing Values in Education) will continue to provide private vouchers to as many children as it can.

<P>
<hr>
<P>

<LI>An ``Inaugural Gala'' on January 22 featured Vice President Al Gore as the keynote speaker and Tipper Gore as presenter of a Lifetime Achievement Award to Robin Chandler Duke of the National Abortion Rights Action League. Pretty brinky to use ``lifetime'' in an award to a person whose ``achievement'' was campaigning to shorten millions of lifetimes to nine months, or less.

<P>
<hr>
<P>

<LI>``I am of Ireland, and the Holy Land of Ireland . . .'' Whether one thinks of Ireland as a holy land or, with some of her angrier sons, as a ``priest-ridden nation,'' one tends to think of her as a Catholic country still. John O'Sullivan's report in these pages a few years ago that Dublin was now scarcely distinguishable from any other European capital came as a shock. But not long afterward voters approved a constitutional change permitting divorce, and the first divorce has now been granted. Banning divorce doesn't necessarily keep marriages intact, as witness the tens of thousands of long-separated couples who signed up to obtain divorces as soon as the referendum passed. But one hopes that in moving into this new era, Ireland will cast an eye (not cold) on the wreckage that America's current no-fault laws have caused, and go slow.


<P>
<hr>
<P><LI>Mexico pays its debt to the U.S., ahead of schedule; we make a cool $500 million in interest; investor confidence is restored. Is it too good to be true? In a word, si. As anyone who has spent time there recently can attest, Mexico is more chaotic than ever. Drug trafficking, violence, and official corruption have never been worse, and despite the rah-rah boosterism that permeates Wall Street generally -- and the <I>Wall Street Journal</I> in particular -- Mexico hasn't begun the privatization and deregulation needed to get its economy moving again. Virtually all the money used to pay the U.S. was borrowed from other lenders at exorbitant interest rates. Our bailout of Mexico two years ago meant, in effect, that we guaranteed the loans Mexico used to pay us off. Meanwhile, the Mexican peso is again overvalued, and the current-account deficit is growing. It may soon be time for another successful rescue.

<P>
<hr>
<P>

<LI>Until recently, no one would have bet that Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien and his Liberal Party would not be easily returned to office in the election expected this year. But this month, Chr&eacutetien's government was forced to make a public apology to Progressive Conservative former Prime Minister Brian Mulroney. In a letter to Swiss government authorities, the Chr&eacutetien government had charged Mulroney and two others with accepting $3.75 million in kickbacks from the sale of Airbus passenger planes to the Canadian national airline in 1988. The accusation was then leaked to the media by the Royal Canadian Mounted Police. While Mulroney is widely said to have presided over the most corrupt government in recent Canadian history, the Liberals have been unable to provide evidence linking him to the Airbus scandal, and they now stand accused of using state power against a political opponent. The right-wing populist Reform Party, which stresses government integrity, is well positioned to benefit and expand its support beyond its western base. With unemployment remaining stubbornly at 10 per cent (despite Chr&eacutetien's promise of ``jobs, jobs, jobs''), defeated Liberals may soon swell the figures.


<P>
<hr>
<P><LI>After so much bad news from the academy, it is a pleasure to hear something very different. At Dartmouth there is traditionally a Christmas-tree-lighting ceremony in the middle of the campus. The Glee Club turns out to sing carols, and many students join them. This December, the administration decreed that no songs with any religious content would be sung. The Glee Club was obliged to make do with ``Frosty the Snowman'' and ``Rudolph the Red-Nosed Reindeer.'' The next night, however, the Glee Club appeared at the tree unofficially and, joined by hundreds of students, sang ``Silent Night,'' ``Hark! the Herald Angels Sing,'' and ``God Rest Ye Merry, Gentlemen.'' This was not the sort of Free Speech that Mario Savio had in mind, no, not at all.


<P>
<hr>
<P>
<LI>The audio of <I>It Takes a Village</I> has been nominated for a Grammy in the category of ``spoken word or non-musical record.'' The book-on-tape is recorded in the First Lady's own voice (if not words).

<P>
<hr>
<P>

<LI>Seen in New Orleans: ``I voted for Mary Landrieu three times and all I got was this lousy T-shirt.''

<P>
<hr>
<P>
<LI>Sam Tanenhaus's new biography of Whittaker Chambers reveals that Chambers was considered as a translator of <I>Remembrance of Things Past</I>. Good thing they didn't use Alger Hiss. ``I do not remember a man by the name of M. Charles Swann.''





<P>
<hr>
<P>


<!------------------------------------------------------------------>
<p>
