</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<BODY bgcolor="#fffff" LINK="red" VLINK="black">
<title>On the Right -- january 27, 1997</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/otr.gif" ALT="On The Right">
<hr>
<BR>
<BR><!------------------------------------------------------------->
<H2>Poor Paula Jones</H2></CENTER>
<HR>
<P>
NEW YORK, JANUARY 14<br>




On the Paula Jones business, what are the points that have crystallized?
<P>
1. If the Court permits the case to proceed against Mr. Clinton, it will not involve the immobilization of the Chief Executive. Justice Souter and again Justice O'Connor said, in various ways, addressing the defendant's attorneys: Look. We are not suggesting that if simultaneously the Paula Jones judge issues a subpoena for the President's appearance and Japan declares war on us, the President will have to go to the courthouse instead of the war room. 
<P>
Driving that point home took rather more time than one would have thought necessary, but after all, it is the open strategy of the defense to argue that the President of the United States simply can't be distracted by long and tedious civil suits while he is in office. 
<P>
2. Some pleasure was to be had from hearing such big-time lawyers as Mr. Robert Bennett going on about the travails of victims of civil suits. The smiling over that one has to do with President Clinton's indenture to the predatory lawyer class which asks for, and often gets, preposterous judgments for relatively trivial offenses. Tort-damage reform has been on the GOP agenda for several years, which resulted in the trial lawyers' association contributing a whopping $2 million to Democratic campaigns. It is fun to hear the representative of a predatory class outline the terrible public consequences of litigious greed. (Mrs. Jones, incidentally, has been asking for $700,000, which is less than one-third of the money Mr. Clinton has already spent in defending himself.)
<P>
3. The behavior of the Emily's List-type ladies is the crowning hypocrisy. These are women who pledged themselves for all time to end the political career of any senator who voted to confirm Clarence Thomas. The reason for this, Emily says, is obvious: Anita Hill was the object of sexual harassment by Clarence Thomas. 
<P>
But how do we know this? one is likely to ask.
<P>
<I>Idiot! We know it because sexual harassment is rife. . . . And because Anita Hill is a Yale graduate, and incapable of lying. . . . And because Clarence Thomas is a conservative and therefore presumptively unreliable. Can't you add up two and two?</I>
<P>
There is some discomfort out there in the feminist ranks over the presumptions against Paula Jones. James Carville understood the situation perfectly when he opined that when you drag a hundred-dollar bill through a trailer park, you come up with such as Paula Jones. It's informative to hear such language from a Tobacco Road populist. 
<P>
But finally,<br>
4. we have to acknowledge that the President of the United States has responsibilities that inevitably give him distinctive protections. Over the weekend viewers could amuse themselves by watching PBS's <I>A Royal Scandal</I>, depicting the fervent sexual activities of a Prince of Wales (not the incumbent). One wonders where Emily was when most needed. Prince George married a Catholic girl and lived with her. Then he went to a mistress. Then he imported a princess from Germany to firm up the blue bloodlines of an heir, which he managed to procreate, but quickly distanced himself from the princess and years later, never mind that she was now ``queen,'' denied her access to his coronation at Westminster. In between he had other mistresses. Wanton love-life is an apanage of the royal class, and we don't mean just King George IV, but also Warren Gamaliel Harding.
<P> 
It is by no means to condone the sexual behavior of Mr. Clinton, pre and post Paula Jones, to accept the realities of presidential eminence. True, Paula Jones was an unwilling vehicle for his lust, and for that reason the Court must not under any circumstances -- indeed, it cannot -- simply make the charges go away. But the compromise everywhere suggested is reasonable: to permit the taking of affidavits while memories are fresh, and wait until the millennium to actually bring the defendant to court. 
<P>
It would have been much easier if my advice had been taken three years ago, which was to raise the $700,000 and give it to Mrs. Jones, with a note saying: We don't agree that Mr. Clinton is guilty, but pending a revision of tort laws, this is cheaper than engaging in a defense against your charges.




<!--------------------------------------------------------------------->
<P>
(<I>Universal Press Syndicate</I>)
