<html>
<head>
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff" LINK="red" VLINK="black">
<title>Letter From Al -- February 10, 1997</title>
</head>
<body>
<p>
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/topletr.gif" ALT="Letter From Al"></center>
<p>
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/dear.gif"></center>
<P>
 <TABLE ALIGN=LEFT width=50%>
<TR>
<TH></TH>
<TD>                                                                





You know what? I'm not sure you missed much by not coming to the Inaugural festivities. In the first place, what could possibly match the 1992 celebration: me and Tip doing our own ``Bring in 'Da Noise, Bring in 'Da Funk'' at the MTV bash, Bill warbling away on the sax, and HRC still a few hours away from identifying the White House Travel Office as the first place to begin reinventing government -- you know, back then we had a sense that the country was turning a corner. 
<P>
A lot of our hopefulness was embodied by Maya Angelou's terrific poem, especially in the lines:
<P> 
The Rock. The Paper. The Scissors. Paper covers Rock. Scissors cut Paper. Rock blunts Scissors.
<P> 
When you think that her poem was a major bestseller for weeks after the 1992 Inauguration, it's hard not to get nostalgic.
<P> 
So this year, it was with a somewhat heavy heart that I took the oath of the office of Vice President for the last time. It'll be nice, I guess, to take the oath of the office of President the next time around, but you know what? It won't be as special. 
<P>
I guess my melancholy attitude comes from something Tipper said last week. You remember, Rusty, that there was a brouhaha in the final days of the campaign about a fundraiser I attended at a Buddhist monastery in California. It turned out that many of the contributions were not quite strictly legal in the most literal and picky definition of the word ``legal,'' and worse, when I said I didn't know at the time that the fundraiser was a fundraiser I wasn't being strictly truthful in the most literal and picky definition of the word ``truthful.''
<P>
``You're turning into him,'' Tipper said, when I showed her the press release which admitted that I had ``fudged'' on the issue.
<P> 
``Who?'' I asked. ``Dad?'' 
<P>
``No, Al. Him. Bill. The kind of guy who lies -- ''
<P>
I cleared my throat. 
<P>
``I'm sorry,'' she went on. ``The kind of guy who fudges so often and about so many small things that he gets the reputation for being a colossal liar -- '' 
<P>
I cleared my throat again.
<P> 
``Okay,'' she said. ``He gets the reputation for being a colossal fudger when what he really is, is a small fudger about a lot of things.''
<P> 
``What's your point, Tip?'' I asked. 





</tr>
</TABLE>
<P>
<TABLE>
<tr>
<TH></TH>
<td>
``My point is, be careful. The press is tired of beating up on Bill. It's too easy. And they're almost tired of beating up on Newt. I mean, the guy is jowly and has bad hair. How challenging is that? It's like hunting dairy cows.''
<P> 
Tipper has a colorful way of phrasing things. But I still didn't get her point. 
<P>
``What are you saying, Tip?'' I asked. ``That the press doesn't like me? Are you kidding? I mean, I hate to toot my own horn, but I'm the only one they do like around here.'' 
<P>
``Uh huh,'' Tip murmured. ``Wait 'til they read about your little white fudge.'' 
<P>
What happened was just as I predicted: we issued the press release, and it ended up somewhere near the ``Land Use Judgments'' section of the Post. The press was still pretty much centered on Gingrich and his ethical problems -- among them, lying about what he knew and when (and he's second in line for the Presidency! Where's the outrage in America?) -- so my little mea culpa was not much noted by some of the White House press corps. (The guy from Newsweek called me ``courageous and forthright''; Time suggested that ``we pause in our outrage that Speaker Gingrich flouted the regulations governing the use of 501(c)(3) funds, and celebrate the Vice President's admission that in the hurly-burly of campaigning, he might have been misunderstood''; and Marty Peretz called to ask if the whole thing wasn't a case of my being so distraught over my sister's death from lung cancer, brought vividly to mind by the incense smoke, that I missed seeing the 67 shoeboxes stuffed with checks and cash. I had to admit his analysis was probably correct.) 
<P>
As I was tying my tie this morning, I joked to Tipper that she had gotten it all wrong, that the press loves me, and that my little fudge didn't signal anything remotely like my becoming Bill. 
<P>
She glowered at me. She hates it when I'm right. But I was having fun, so I pressed on. 
<P>
``I mean, it's not me that we have to worry about, Tip. It's you. You know what I think? I think you're becoming a little bit like her. That's what I think.'' 
Chuckling, I slipped the knot in my tie and glanced in the mirror. I barely saw her pick up the lamp. 
<P>
So whatever it was, the weather, the smaller crowd, or the throbbing pain on the left side of my head, all I can say is, I enjoyed 1992 a lot more. 
<P>
See you soon, Rusty.


</TD>
</tr>
</TABLE>

<P>
<br>
<TABLE WIDTH=25%>
<tr>
<TH></TH>
