<html>
<head>
<title>Universal IRAs Increase After-Tax Incomes</title> <body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h1><center>How Universal, Unlimited, Tax-Deductible IRAs Will Increase 
After-Tax Incomes In the Year 2000</center></h1> 
<p>
<pre>
		Adjusted Gross			Percent Change In
		    Income			After-Tax Income
                --------------			-----------------

		Under $5,000				0.2%
             $ 5,000 - $10,000                          3.4%
	      10,000 -  20,000			       13.6%
	      20,000 -  30,000			       19.3%
	      30,000 -  40,000			       12.4%
	      40,000 -  50,000			       12.3%
	      50,000 - 100,000			       23.3%
	     100,000 - 200,000				6.3%
	     200,000 - 500,000				3.3%
	     500,000 or more				5.8%

</pre>
In the year 2000, it is estimated that the after-tax income of taxpayers, 
under its current definition, will be increased by $151 billion due to 
the added growth generated by universal IRAs.  Furthermore, most of that 
gain in after-tax income - 85% - will go to taxpayers with incomes under 
$100,000, and over 60% will go to people with $50,000 or less of adjusted 
gross income.  Additionally, the bulk of the percentage change in 
after-tax incomes will flow to those taxpayers with adjusted gross 
incomes between $10,000 and $100,000.  The percentage increase in the 
after-tax income for taxpayers within these classes ranges between 12% 
and 23%.<br>
<p>
The above table clearly portrays a dramatic improvement in everyone's 
standard of living, <i>and particularly those in middle-income 
America</i>.  These results, which will grow as the IRA assets grow, are 
directly derived from the enactment of universal IRA legislation.<br>

<p>
<hr>
<p>
<b>NOTE:</b> The above table was taken from a study commissioned by the 
Savers &amp; 
Investors League by the respected consulting firm of Fiscal Associates, 
Inc..  In that study, they addressed the future dynamic gains to be 
derived from the enactment of universal, unlimited, tax-deductible 
IRA-type legislation.  The study was completed in 1993 and all subsequent 
yearly figures were calculated assuming the enacted legislation would 
have occurred in 1993.<br>
<p>
<hr>
