<HEAD>
<title>Labor Watch</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<blockquote>
<table><tr><td>
<img src="/sbsc/hdr-lw.gif"></td>
<td><h4><center>
a weekly summary of labor movement<br>
activity and Clinton Administration initiatives<br>
that advance big labor's agenda<br>
</center></h4>
</td></tr></table>
<hr> 
<h3>Table of Contents</h3>
<P>
<ul>
<li><a href="#one">Big Labor : Biggest Losers of '96 Elections</a>
<li><a href="#two">Calling a "Salt" a "Salt"</a>
<li><a href="#three">Sweeney's Hangover</a>
</ul><p>
<CENTER>November 6, 1996 published by the Small
Business Survival FoundationVolume I, Issue 27<BR>
</CENTER>
<hr>
<P>
<a name="one"></a>
<CENTER><B>Big Labor: Biggest Losers of '96
Elections<BR>
</B></CENTER>
<P>
The Small Business Survival (SBS) Foundation released
a report Oct. 31 asking the question, "Will
Sweeney Sink or Save Labor?"
 The new report concludes: "Under
AFL-CIO President John Sweeney, big labor will be a big loser."
<P>
The report lays out the long decline of labor union
membership and the increasing share of government employees in
labor union ranks.  SBS Foundation forecasts, based on recent
trends, that public-sector employees account for 42% of union
membership, up from a mere 6% in 1960.  As a percent of private
and public workforces, private-sector union membership is in free
fall, while public-sector unionism has stagnated for several years.
<P>
"This trend is not lost on union leaders like Sweeney,"
says SBS Foundation president Karen Kerrigan.  "Big
labor's
massive campaign against Republican members of Congress who favored
spending restraint and market-based policies are antithetical
to the labor movement's
need for coercive government to assist in their organizing efforts,
while propping up their relevancy.  With Republicans keeping control
of Congress, big labor's
failed efforts to reelect a Democrat majority will go down in
history as one of the most wasteful and unsuccessful political
campaigns of the twentieth century.  Labor leaders should have
focused on the task at hand:
building membership and representing the authentic concerns of
its members.  Sweeney is doing neither."
<P>
The report's
author, Raymond J. Keating, SBS Foundation Chief Economist, notes:
"In
an economy where entrepreneurship is on the rise, competition
is intensifying, and technological advancements are bringing about
further decentralization, big labor's
preferences for high taxes, excessive regulation, protectionism,
larger government, and class warfare make no sense.  In addition,
Sweeney's
strategic alignment with other groups in demise, like social activists
of the 1960s variety 
(socialists, left-wing academics, and various big-government groups)
 will only speed, rather than slow, the decline of labor unions.
 I guess misery does love company."
<P>
For a copy of "Will
Sweeney Sink or Save Labor?"
Please call SBS Foundation at 202-785-0238.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<a name="two"></a>
<CENTER><B>Calling a "Salt" a "Salt"
<BR>
</B></CENTER>
<P>
The pernicious union corporate campaign tactic known
as salting was wounded recently by an administrative law judge
(ALJ) in San Francisco.  In a decision involving Irwin Industries,
the ALJ held that filing "frivolous,
knowingly false"
charges was "an
integral part of the . . . 'fight
back'
strategy that was contrived to force the company to spend substantial
amounts of money defending itself before the"
National Labor Relations Board (NLRB). 
<P>
The company had hired known Boilermakers Union organizers
in the past, but they had never been a target of "salting"
activity.  However, after an organizer was hired as a supervisor
on a new job, and asked to sign a statement that  asserted "I
am here for the best interest of IRWIN INDUSTRIES, INC. AND NOT
for the benefit of the [boilermakers] . . .," 
he initiated the campaign.
<P>
The organizer and his supporters engaged in a work
slowdown and were subsequently fired for that activity.  Afterwords
a busload of applicants appeared at the company office where they
filled out job applications and wrote the words "voluntary
organizers"
at the top.  The NLRB issued a complaint alleging unlawful discharges
against the organizer and his cohorts, and unlawful refusal to
hire the "volunteer
organizers."
<P>
The judge dismissed the complaint.  He went on to
recommend that the NLRB impose a remedy on the union which blocks
the future filing of bogus charges against the employer.<BR>
<P>
<a name="three"></a>
<CENTER><B>Sweeney's
Hangover<BR>
</B></CENTER>
<P>
In a <I>Washington Times</I> piece today (November
6 1996) called "Wednesday
hangover,"
AFL-CIO Chief John Sweeney may have taken too much liberty with
rank-and-file dues.
<P>
According to the report:
<P>
<I>
". .class-action lawyers are looking into suing the AFL-CIO on
behalf of its members to return to them the $35 million in dues
that union President John Sweeney spent trying to elect a Democratic
House of Representatives.
<P>
Any such suit could cripple the AFL-CIO for years,
one legal expert suggests.
<P>
Ironically, class-action suits are lucrative for
lawyers and are protected by the liberal Democrats Mr. Sweeney
supports."</I>
<P>
It looks as though shrewd lawyers have figured out
that fewer lawsuit opportunities will be available as the GOP
will likely make another attempt at legal reform.  And with fewer
new regulations and rules being signed into law- 
as is expected to be the case with the new Congress-
why not go after labor unions?
<P>
<I>The massive partisan political campaign waged
against the GOP in the '96
elections, only resulted in 14 GOP freshmen scalps for John Sweeney.</I>
<BR>
<p>
<center>
| <a href="/sbsc/">Home</a> | <a href="/sbsc/laborwatch/welcome.html">Labor Watch Index</a> | </center>
<p><br>
</body>
