<TITLE>Carolyn and Keating</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="/sbsc/sbsmall.gif">
<P>
<center>
<h2>
Carolan & Keating - November 11, 1996<BR>
Bond Act on the Brain and Time for Big Al's Exit
<BR>
</h2>
<P>
<h3>
by Matthew Carolan and Raymond J. Keating<BR>
</h3>
</center>
<P>
<BR>
<blockquote>
<DD><FONT SIZE=+2>T</FONT>he scene is a Manhattan hotel on election night at five minutes to nine.  Governor George Pataki is questioned about the Dole campaign by a local reporter. He answers by talking about the importance of his environmental bond act.  
<P>
Pataki is asked the question again.  The answer, once more, relates to the bond act.  When pressed another time, Pataki explains that the Dole camp "pulled out of New York about a month ago," so there was nothing that could be done.  Then, the Governor returns to the bond act.
<P>     
Those who read this column know that we have been generally supportive of George Pataki. We believe his tax cuts, for example, are a vital step to regaining New York's economic health.  We applaud Pataki's efforts to reform the worker's compensation system and lifting some regulations in the health-care arena.  But the Governor's behavior these past few months -- his myopic campaigning for the pork-barrel bond act especially -- raises serious doubts about both his strategic thinking and leadership regarding conservative ideas. 
<P>     
Forget the Dole campaign, which had it's own problems.  But what about the State Assembly races?  For months, many conservatives and Republicans have argued that winning the Assembly was vital to getting smaller government in New York.  Yet, with barely a peep from the Governor this fall, the GOP actually lost a few seats in the state legislature overall.
<P>     
Perhaps we should have seen the lack of leadership coming. Recall that last year, during another delayed budget, the Governor failed to bring that fight for smaller government to the mass media.  Now the Governor has traded his shot at a majority in the Assembly for personal image polishing with the Greens.  He is also rarely seen in Albany.  Such clear lack of strategic focus or zeal at the top of the GOP is surely not lost on Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver, Democrat Chairwoman Judith Hope, or the handful of Democrats who seem eager to run for governor in 1998.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=30% ALIGN=left SIZE=3>
<P>
 <DD><FONT SIZE=+2>I</FONT>s it our imagination or does Senator Al D'Amato become less and less subtle about his political opportunism with each passing day?
<P>    
After Bill Clinton scored big in New York, including heavily Republican Nassau County, Senator Al D'Amato made a remarkably transparent attempt to mend his reputation by suggesting maybe it's time to call a truce on Whitewater.  What irony, the most political Republican of all now reinforces the perception that the Whitewater investigations were always political by calling them off after the election.  This leaves the rest of D'Amato's party to answer the false charge of politicization, leading one Republican staffer to comment "Typical D'Amato. CYA." (Cover your a--).  
<P>
D'Amato performed a similar turnabout on primary night earlier this year.  After victoriously using the New York GOP's rigged primary rules for his own candidate, D'Amato called for eliminating those very rules in favor of a more open system.
<P>
     D'Amato's brazenness lies in the fact that everything he touches is political.  He poisoned Whitewater. He poisoned the bond act. He has poisoned George Pataki's reputation.  Nothing Al D'Amato does or says can be taken at face value.  Everything must be scrutinized for its underlying meaning.  Next time he holds a press conference to announce he's in love, listen carefully, there may be federal funding involved.
<P>     
We just wonder how much longer the GOP family will put up with brazen Al D'Amato.  How many losing candidates this year, for example, will work hard for King Al's re-election in 1998 after he left them to twist in the wind while he hawked the bond act?  Will many of these same local hacks continue to say "Yes boss," while enduring another of D'Amato's acid phone calls?
<P>
However, it's simply not a question of process with D'Amato any longer.  His political judgment must come into serious question in 1996, after appearing so astute in 1994.  After all, D'Amato led the early charge for Bob Dole.  D'Amato lined up every elected New York Republican official (barring Rudy Giuliani who came to Dole of his own accord much later) behind one of the most inept GOP presidential candidates ever.  D'Amato will attempt to blame the Dole loss on extremists in his party (some of D'Amato's local hacks started spinning this thesis on election night).  However, in reality, it was largely GOP liberals and moderates like D'Amato who pushed Bob Dole to the forefront.
<P>     
We wonder: Isn't there anybody in the whole New York GOP who will stand up and primary Al D'Amato -- some former Ambassador, some retired executive?  Is there no bond trader or investment banker in the state who refuses to kiss D'Amato's you-know-what?  Somebody who can't be bought with a patronage job, or who cares more about policy and economic freedom than pork.  Of course, there are some, but alas D'Amato controls the GOP patronage machine -- at least until 1998.  Post-1998 is when things might get interesting for New York Republicans.
<P>
<BR>
<BR><hr>
<CENTER><FONT  SIZE=-1>Matthew Carolan is executive editor of National Review.  <BR>Raymond
J. Keating serves as chief economist for the Small Business Survival
Committee. <BR>The views expressed are their own.  <BR>Copyright 1996.
</FONT><BR>
<p>
<center></CENTER>
</blockquote>
