<P>
<center>
<h2>
Carolan & Keating -- September 16, 1996<BR>
Any Real Conservatives in New York?<BR>
</h2>
<P>
<h3>
by Matthew Carolan and Raymond J. Keating<BR>
</h3>
</center>
<P>
<blockquote>
In recent years, a few skirmishes seem to have broken out on the
conservative side of the political aisle.  Many in the media,
of course, have portrayed this as an epic war on the right between
social conservatives and economic conservatives.
<P>
Like most true conservatives, we fail to see what all the fuss
is about.  We're both economically and socially conservative &#173;&#173;
supply&#173;side, pro&#173;family, free&#173;trade, pro&#173;life,
hawkish, internationalist, property&#173;rights, small&#173;government
conservatives.
<P>
The controversy arises when self&#173;proclaimed &quot;conservative&quot;
politicians turn out, in reality, to be moderates or fence&#173;sitters.
 New York and the rest of the Northeast are full of such impersonators.
 Indeed, Governors Bill Weld (Massachusetts), Christie Whitman
(New Jersey), John Rowland (Connecticut), and New York's own George
Pataki, all claim to be conservatives.  However, their records
and positions show each to be mild economic and fiscal conservatives,
while being quite liberal on many social issues, most prominently
on abortion.
<P>
On the flip side, Pat Buchanan claims the mantle of conservatism
as well.  But in reality, Buchanan turns out only to be conservative
on social issues, while on the economics front he has become a
raving class warrior, touting the liberal, big&#173;labor line
on issues like trade and immigration.
<P>
This division between Buchananites and middle&#173;of&#173;the&#173;road
Republicans turns out not really to be a battle on the right at
all, but a fight between two very confused camps within the Republican
Party.  One side fails to understand the value of human life while
the other misunderstands the value of free, unfettered markets.
 Neither are conservative in a complete sense.
<P>
To get a sense of how truly conservative the New York congressional
delegation is, C&amp;K turned to two sources.  The Christian Coalition,
a pro&#173;family group with more than 1.7 million members, rated
the 104th Congress according to 13 key votes in the House of Representatives
and 11 key votes in the Senate.  These votes offer a good representation
of socially conservative issues, from abortion to welfare reform
to school vouchers to tax cuts.  The Small Business Survival Committee
(SBSC), a pro&#173;entrepreneur, pro&#173;free market advocacy
group with more than 40,000 small business members (C&amp;K's
Keating serves as chief economist for SBSC), rated Congress according
to 25 key votes in the House and 18 key votes in the Senate. 
The issues ranged from deregulation to private property rights
to spending reductions to tax cuts &#173;&#173; a good representation
of conservative economic issues.  
<P>
Indeed, as any good conservative would expect, the two organizations
had some overlap in terms of the issues on which Members of Congress
were rated.  Each group used a scoring system whereby 100 rated
best and 0 rated worst.  In the accompanying chart, C&amp;K combined
the two scores to arrive at a gauge for the complete conservative,
and ranked New York's congressional delegation accordingly.  A
perfect score is 200.
<P>
Not to our surprise, no New York Member of Congress scored a perfect
200, though three House Members impressively scored in the 190s.
 These three &#173;&#173; Solomon, Frisa, and Paxon &#173;&#173;
are all Republicans.  Gilman, Houghton, and worst of all, Boelhert
rated least conservative among New York GOPers in the House.
<P>
No Democrats scored well.  The least liberal, you might say, was
McNulty in the House, followed by LaFalce and Manton.  Ackerman,
Hinchey, and Serrano scored perfectly liberal zeros.
<P>
As for the Senate, Al D'Amato scored slightly favorable on the
conservative meter, and Pat Moynihan miserably.
<P>
Obviously, these ratings are not comprehensive, in that they reflect
only select key votes.  But they do give the reader a feeling
of where their elected officials generally come down  &#173;&#173;
left or right &#173;&#173; on the issues.
<P>
Overall, New York's congressional delegation rates very liberal.
 Indeed, in our view, the Empire State can claim only one or two
across&#173;the&#173;board principled conservatives in Congress.
 Meanwhile, little more can be said at the state level, with a
handful of principled conservatives in the Assembly and none to
be found among state senators, the Governor or the Lieutenant
Governor.
<P>
Of course, this dearth of true conservatism explains why New York
ranks among the worst in the nation in areas like taxes, government
spending, entrepreneurship, job creation, and abortions.<BR>
<P>
New York's Congressional Delegation
<P>
